{"title_page": "Code on Wages, 2019", "text_new": "{{use dmy dates|date=August 2019}}\n{{use Indian English|date=August 2019}}\n{{Infobox legislation\n| short_title = The Code on Wages, 2019\n| legislature = [[Parliament of India]]\n| imagesize = 100\n| long_title = An Act to amend and consolidate the laws relating to wages and bonus and matters connected therewith or incidental thereto.\nIn forced from 21 Nov 2019.\n| citation = [http://egazette.nic.in/WriteReadData/2019/210356.pdf Act No. 29 of 2019]\n| territorial_extent = India\n| enacted_by = [[Lok Sabha]]\n| date_enacted = \n| date_passed = 30 July 2019\n| enacted_by2 = [[Rajya Sabha]]\n| date_passed2 = 2 August 2019\n| date_assented = 8 August 2019\n| date_commenced = \n| bill = The Code on Wages Bill, 2019\n| bill_citation = [http://164.100.47.4/BillsTexts/LSBillTexts/Asintroduced/184_2019_LS_Eng.pdf Bill No. 184 of 2019]\n| bill_date = 23 July 2019\n| introduced_by = [[Santosh Gangwar]]\n| 1st_reading = Has been commenced in force as law  by Notification published on official site of Central labour Commissioner of gov of India.\nNow it is mandatory for every sector either private or government or public sector\n| 2nd_reading = \n| 3rd_reading = \n| committee_report = Report of the Parliamentary Standing Committee\n| date_conf_committee = 18 December 2018\n| repeals = {{ubl|Payment of Wages Act, 1936|[[Minimum Wages Act 1948|Minimum Wages Act, 1948]]|Payment of Bonus Act, 1965|Equal Remuneration Act, 1976}}\n| summary = \n| keywords = \n| status = In forced by notification dated 21.11.2019.\n}}\n'''The Code on Wages, 2019''', also known as the '''Wage Code''', is an [[Act of Parliament|Act]] of the [[Parliament of India]] that consolidates the provisions of four [[Labour law|labour laws]] concerning wage and bonus payments and makes universal the provisions for [[minimum wage]]<nowiki/>s and timely payment of wages for all workers in India.\n\n==Background==\n{{see|Indian labour law}}\nThe [[Narendra Modi]] administration began considering a plan in 2015 to consolidate India's 44 labour laws into four codes in order to rationalize labour laws and improve [[Ease of doing business index|ease of doing business]]. Finance Minister [[Nirmala Sitharaman]] stated in her [[2019 Union budget of India|2019 Union Budget]] speech, \"This will ensure that process of registration and filing of returns will get standardised and streamlined. With various labour related definitions getting standardised, it is expected that there shall be less dispute.\" The Code on Wages is the first of the proposed codes. The other three are the [[Occupational Safety, Health and Working Conditions Code, 2019|Occupational Safety, Health and Working Conditions Code]], the Code on Industrial Relations, and the Code on Social Security.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Sharma |first1=Yogima Seth |title=Lok Sabha passes Wage Code Bill to ensure minimum wage for workers |url=https://economictimes.indiatimes.com/news/politics-and-nation/lok-sabha-passes-wage-code-bill-to-ensure-minimum-wage-for-workers/articleshow/70453233.cms |website=The Economic Times |accessdate=10 August 2019 |date=30 July 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Legislative history==\n''The Code on Wages Bill'' was introduced in the [[Lok Sabha]] on 10 August 2017 by the [[Minister of State]] for [[Ministry of Labour and Employment (India)|Labour and Employment]] (Independent Charge), [[Santosh Gangwar]]. The bill was referred to a Parliamentary Standing Committee on 21 August 2017. The Committee submitted its report on 18 December 2018.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Katiyar |first1=Prerna |title=What Code on Wages means for the 50 crore workers it aims to benefit |url=https://economictimes.indiatimes.com/news/economy/policy/decoded-what-code-on-wages-mean-for-the-50-crore-workers-it-aims-to-benefit/articleshow/70515807.cms |website=The Economic Times |accessdate=10 August 2019 |date=4 August 2019}}</ref> The Committee made 24 recommendations, of which 17 were incorporated into the bill.<ref name = \"Hindu\">{{cite web |title=Lok Sabha passes Wage Code Bill to ensure minimum wage for workers |url=https://www.thehindu.com/news/national/lok-sabha-passes-wage-code-bill-to-ensure-minimum-wage-for-workers/article28761226.ece |website=The Hindu |accessdate=10 August 2019 |language=en-IN |date=30 July 2019}}</ref><ref name = \"PIB LS\">{{cite web |title=Lok Sabha Passes the Code on Wages Bill, 2019 |url=http://pib.nic.in/newsite/PrintRelease.aspx?relid=192386 |website=pib.nic.in |accessdate=10 August 2019}}</ref>  The bill lapsed following the dissolution of the [[16th Lok Sabha]] ahead of the [[2019 Indian general election|2019 general elections]]. ''The Code on Wages Bill, 2019'' was re-introduced in the House on 23 July 2019.<ref name = \"Hindu\"/><ref>{{cite web |title=The Code on Wages, 2019 |url=https://www.prsindia.org/billtrack/code-wages-2019 |website=PRSIndia |accessdate=10 August 2019 |language=en |date=23 July 2019}}</ref>\n\nMoving the bill for consideration, Gangwar stated that the government had held consultations with [[Trade unions in India|trade unions]], employers and [[State governments of India|State governments]], and held tripartite consultations on 10 March 2015 and 13 April 2015. He also stated that a draft of the bill was made available on the [[Ministry of Labour and Employment (India)|Ministry of Labour and Employment]]'s website and suggestions from the general public were taken into account.<ref name = \"PIB LS\"/> Gangwar added that existing labour laws only governed payment of wages for about 40% of the labour force and the Code on Wages would extend coverage to the entire labour force irrespective of sector or wage ceiling. He noted that provisions on timely payment of wages would bring relief to workers in the unorganized sector of the economy.<ref name = \"Hindu\"/> The bill was passed by the Lok Sabha on 30 July 2019.<ref>{{cite web |title=Lok Sabha passes Code on Wages Bill, 2019 |url=https://www.aninews.in/news/national/politics/lok-sabha-passes-code-on-wages-bill-201920190730214848/ |website=www.aninews.in |accessdate=10 August 2019 |language=en}}</ref> \n\nThe bill was passed by the Rajya Sabha on 2 August 2019.<ref>{{cite web |title=Rajya Sabha Passes The Code on Wages Bill, 2019 |url=http://pib.nic.in/newsite/PrintRelease.aspx?relid=192463 |website=pib.nic.in |accessdate=10 August 2019}}</ref> The bill received assent from President [[Ram Nath Kovind]] on 8 August, and was notified in ''[[The Gazette of India]]'' on the same date.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://egazette.nic.in/WriteReadData/2019/210356.pdf |title=Gazette facsimile |date=8 August 2019 |website=egazette.nic.in |format=PDF |access-date=2019-08-19}}</ref>\n\n==Coverage==\nThe Code Of Wages, 2019 is applicable to employees in organised sector and unorganised sector, while the central government will continue to make wage related decisions for railways, mines, oil fields, and central public sector undertakings.<ref>https://labour.gov.in/sites/default/files/THE%20CODE%20ON%20WAGES%2C%202019%20No.%2029%20of%202019.pdf</ref>. It subsumes The Payment of Wages Act, 1936;[[Minimum Wages Act 1948|The Minimum Wages Act, 1948]];The Payment of Bonus Act, 1965; and The Equal Renumeration Act, 1976. <ref>https://pib.gov.in/newsite/PrintRelease.aspx?relid=192386</ref> through following chapters:\n\u2022Preliminary\n\u2022Minimum Wages\n\u2022Payment of Wages\n\u2022Payment of Bonus\n\u2022Advisory Board\n\u2022Payment of Dues, Claims and Audit\n\u2022Inspector cum Facilitator\n\u2022Offences and Penalties\n\u2022Miscellaneous\n<ref>https://labour.gov.in/sites/default/files/THE%20CODE%20ON%20WAGES%2C%202019%20No.%2029%20of%202019.pdf</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n[[Category:Indian labour law]]\n[[Category:2019 in Indian law]]\n[[Category:Minimum wage law]]\n", "text_old": "{{use dmy dates|date=August 2019}}\n{{use Indian English|date=August 2019}}\n{{Infobox legislation\n| short_title = The Code on Wages, 2019\n| legislature = [[Parliament of India]]\n| imagesize = 100\n| long_title = An Act to amend and consolidate the laws relating to wages and bonus and matters connected therewith or incidental thereto.\n| citation = [http://egazette.nic.in/WriteReadData/2019/210356.pdf Act No. 29 of 2019]\n| territorial_extent = India\n| enacted_by = [[Lok Sabha]]\n| date_enacted = \n| date_passed = 30 July 2019\n| enacted_by2 = [[Rajya Sabha]]\n| date_passed2 = 2 August 2019\n| date_assented = 8 August 2019\n| date_commenced = \n| bill = The Code on Wages Bill, 2019\n| bill_citation = [http://164.100.47.4/BillsTexts/LSBillTexts/Asintroduced/184_2019_LS_Eng.pdf Bill No. 184 of 2019]\n| bill_date = 23 July 2019\n| introduced_by = [[Santosh Gangwar]]\n| 1st_reading = \n| 2nd_reading = \n| 3rd_reading = \n| committee_report = Report of the Parliamentary Standing Committee\n| date_conf_committee = 18 December 2018\n| repeals = {{ubl|Payment of Wages Act, 1936|[[Minimum Wages Act 1948|Minimum Wages Act, 1948]]|Payment of Bonus Act, 1965|Equal Remuneration Act, 1976}}\n| summary = \n| keywords = \n| status = In forced by notification dated 21.11.2019.\n}}\n'''The Code on Wages, 2019''', also known as the '''Wage Code''', is an [[Act of Parliament|Act]] of the [[Parliament of India]] that consolidates the provisions of four [[Labour law|labour laws]] concerning wage and bonus payments and makes universal the provisions for [[minimum wage]]<nowiki/>s and timely payment of wages for all workers in India.\n\n==Background==\n{{see|Indian labour law}}\nThe [[Narendra Modi]] administration began considering a plan in 2015 to consolidate India's 44 labour laws into four codes in order to rationalize labour laws and improve [[Ease of doing business index|ease of doing business]]. Finance Minister [[Nirmala Sitharaman]] stated in her [[2019 Union budget of India|2019 Union Budget]] speech, \"This will ensure that process of registration and filing of returns will get standardised and streamlined. With various labour related definitions getting standardised, it is expected that there shall be less dispute.\" The Code on Wages is the first of the proposed codes. The other three are the [[Occupational Safety, Health and Working Conditions Code, 2019|Occupational Safety, Health and Working Conditions Code]], the Code on Industrial Relations, and the Code on Social Security.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Sharma |first1=Yogima Seth |title=Lok Sabha passes Wage Code Bill to ensure minimum wage for workers |url=https://economictimes.indiatimes.com/news/politics-and-nation/lok-sabha-passes-wage-code-bill-to-ensure-minimum-wage-for-workers/articleshow/70453233.cms |website=The Economic Times |accessdate=10 August 2019 |date=30 July 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Legislative history==\n''The Code on Wages Bill'' was introduced in the [[Lok Sabha]] on 10 August 2017 by the [[Minister of State]] for [[Ministry of Labour and Employment (India)|Labour and Employment]] (Independent Charge), [[Santosh Gangwar]]. The bill was referred to a Parliamentary Standing Committee on 21 August 2017. The Committee submitted its report on 18 December 2018.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Katiyar |first1=Prerna |title=What Code on Wages means for the 50 crore workers it aims to benefit |url=https://economictimes.indiatimes.com/news/economy/policy/decoded-what-code-on-wages-mean-for-the-50-crore-workers-it-aims-to-benefit/articleshow/70515807.cms |website=The Economic Times |accessdate=10 August 2019 |date=4 August 2019}}</ref> The Committee made 24 recommendations, of which 17 were incorporated into the bill.<ref name = \"Hindu\">{{cite web |title=Lok Sabha passes Wage Code Bill to ensure minimum wage for workers |url=https://www.thehindu.com/news/national/lok-sabha-passes-wage-code-bill-to-ensure-minimum-wage-for-workers/article28761226.ece |website=The Hindu |accessdate=10 August 2019 |language=en-IN |date=30 July 2019}}</ref><ref name = \"PIB LS\">{{cite web |title=Lok Sabha Passes the Code on Wages Bill, 2019 |url=http://pib.nic.in/newsite/PrintRelease.aspx?relid=192386 |website=pib.nic.in |accessdate=10 August 2019}}</ref>  The bill lapsed following the dissolution of the [[16th Lok Sabha]] ahead of the [[2019 Indian general election|2019 general elections]]. ''The Code on Wages Bill, 2019'' was re-introduced in the House on 23 July 2019.<ref name = \"Hindu\"/><ref>{{cite web |title=The Code on Wages, 2019 |url=https://www.prsindia.org/billtrack/code-wages-2019 |website=PRSIndia |accessdate=10 August 2019 |language=en |date=23 July 2019}}</ref>\n\nMoving the bill for consideration, Gangwar stated that the government had held consultations with [[Trade unions in India|trade unions]], employers and [[State governments of India|State governments]], and held tripartite consultations on 10 March 2015 and 13 April 2015. He also stated that a draft of the bill was made available on the [[Ministry of Labour and Employment (India)|Ministry of Labour and Employment]]'s website and suggestions from the general public were taken into account.<ref name = \"PIB LS\"/> Gangwar added that existing labour laws only governed payment of wages for about 40% of the labour force and the Code on Wages would extend coverage to the entire labour force irrespective of sector or wage ceiling. He noted that provisions on timely payment of wages would bring relief to workers in the unorganized sector of the economy.<ref name = \"Hindu\"/> The bill was passed by the Lok Sabha on 30 July 2019.<ref>{{cite web |title=Lok Sabha passes Code on Wages Bill, 2019 |url=https://www.aninews.in/news/national/politics/lok-sabha-passes-code-on-wages-bill-201920190730214848/ |website=www.aninews.in |accessdate=10 August 2019 |language=en}}</ref> \n\nThe bill was passed by the Rajya Sabha on 2 August 2019.<ref>{{cite web |title=Rajya Sabha Passes The Code on Wages Bill, 2019 |url=http://pib.nic.in/newsite/PrintRelease.aspx?relid=192463 |website=pib.nic.in |accessdate=10 August 2019}}</ref> The bill received assent from President [[Ram Nath Kovind]] on 8 August, and was notified in ''[[The Gazette of India]]'' on the same date.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://egazette.nic.in/WriteReadData/2019/210356.pdf |title=Gazette facsimile |date=8 August 2019 |website=egazette.nic.in |format=PDF |access-date=2019-08-19}}</ref>\n\n==Coverage==\nThe Code Of Wages, 2019 is applicable to employees in organised sector and unorganised sector, while the central government will continue to make wage related decisions for railways, mines, oil fields, and central public sector undertakings.<ref>https://labour.gov.in/sites/default/files/THE%20CODE%20ON%20WAGES%2C%202019%20No.%2029%20of%202019.pdf</ref>. It subsumes The Payment of Wages Act, 1936;[[Minimum Wages Act 1948|The Minimum Wages Act, 1948]];The Payment of Bonus Act, 1965; and The Equal Renumeration Act, 1976. <ref>https://pib.gov.in/newsite/PrintRelease.aspx?relid=192386</ref> through following chapters:\n\u2022Preliminary\n\u2022Minimum Wages\n\u2022Payment of Wages\n\u2022Payment of Bonus\n\u2022Advisory Board\n\u2022Payment of Dues, Claims and Audit\n\u2022Inspector cum Facilitator\n\u2022Offences and Penalties\n\u2022Miscellaneous\n<ref>https://labour.gov.in/sites/default/files/THE%20CODE%20ON%20WAGES%2C%202019%20No.%2029%20of%202019.pdf</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n[[Category:Indian labour law]]\n[[Category:2019 in Indian law]]\n[[Category:Minimum wage law]]\n", "name_user": "AdityaManthan", "label": "safe", "comment": "Has been commenced in force as law  by Notification published on official site of Central labour Commissioner of gov of India. Now it is mandatory for every sector either private or government or public sector", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Code_on_Wages,_2019"}
